We'll talk a little bit
about with gold and dollars

00:02:44.450 --> 00:02:46.320 align:middle line:90%
as well with regard to that.

00:02:46.320 --> 00:02:48.860 align:middle line:84%
But what ended up
happening was that

00:02:48.860 --> 00:02:52.430 align:middle line:84%
because an overwhelming
amount of those stocks

00:02:52.430 --> 00:02:58.040 align:middle line:84%
is owned by the very wealthy,
the money that was lent out

00:02:58.040 --> 00:03:02.600 align:middle line:84%
to address COVID all went
into hedge funds and Wall

00:03:02.600 --> 00:03:04.307 align:middle line:90%
Street and not Main Street.

00:03:04.307 --> 00:03:06.140 align:middle line:84%
We're going to talk a
little bit about that.

00:03:06.140 --> 00:03:06.560 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Well, we are.

00:03:06.560 --> 00:03:07.320 align:middle line:90%
That's important.

00:03:07.320 --> 00:03:08.445 align:middle line:90%
That's where that bailout--

00:03:08.445 --> 00:03:09.680 align:middle line:90%
if anybody is paying--

00:03:09.680 --> 00:03:14.180 align:middle line:84%
was paying attention when those
first bailouts came in 2020,

00:03:14.180 --> 00:03:17.570 align:middle line:84%
the first $1.4 trillion
went to Wall Street.

00:03:17.570 --> 00:03:19.695 align:middle line:84%
Not to the people, not
for any social services,

00:03:19.695 --> 00:03:20.495 align:middle line:90%
not for medical.

00:03:20.495 --> 00:03:21.110 align:middle line:84%
>>YIAMOUYIANNIS:
Corporations in Wall Street.

00:03:21.110 --> 00:03:23.040 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Corporations in
Wall Street, big corporations.

00:03:23.040 --> 00:03:24.998 align:middle line:84%
>>YIAMOUYIANNIS: And now
they can leverage that

00:03:24.998 --> 00:03:27.260 align:middle line:84%
to a factor of four or
five, so you basically

00:03:27.260 --> 00:03:30.710 align:middle line:84%
gave them an infusion of
liquidity amounting to anywhere

00:03:30.710 --> 00:03:32.600 align:middle line:90%
from $4 to $7 trillion.

00:03:32.600 --> 00:03:35.540 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well, this has shown
in how much their wealth has

00:03:35.540 --> 00:03:37.040 align:middle line:84%
grown over the last
year and a half.

00:03:37.040 --> 00:03:38.082 align:middle line:90%
>>YIAMOUYIANNIS: Exactly.

00:03:38.082 --> 00:03:41.450 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Skyrocketing while
everyone else is tanking.

00:03:41.450 --> 00:03:43.250 align:middle line:84%
Not everyone, but a
lot of the top sectors.

00:03:43.250 --> 00:03:44.750 align:middle line:84%
>>YIAMOUYIANNIS:
Billionaires alone,

00:03:44.750 --> 00:03:47.330 align:middle line:84%
we're talking a handful
of people, 400 families,

00:03:47.330 --> 00:03:51.590 align:middle line:84%
billionaires, were making
trillions during the biggest

00:03:51.590 --> 00:03:52.820 align:middle line:90%
downturn--

00:03:52.820 --> 00:03:53.780 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Since the
Great Depression.

00:03:53.780 --> 00:03:54.890 align:middle line:84%
>>YIAMOUYIANNIS: --since
the Great Depression.

00:03:54.890 --> 00:03:56.807 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Now, let me
ask you something, Zeus.

00:03:56.807 --> 00:03:59.210 align:middle line:84%
Did that mirror the
Great Depression?

00:03:59.210 --> 00:04:01.652 align:middle line:84%
Was there extreme
wealth that was

00:04:01.652 --> 00:04:03.485 align:middle line:84%
being leveraged during
the Great Depression?

00:04:03.485 --> 00:04:03.980 align:middle line:90%
>>YIAMOUYIANNIS: No.

00:04:03.980 --> 00:04:05.060 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: It wasn't the same.

00:04:05.060 --> 00:04:05.940 align:middle line:84%
>>YIAMOUYIANNIS:
No, the reason why

00:04:05.940 --> 00:04:07.400 align:middle line:84%
you had so many people
committing suicides

00:04:07.400 --> 00:04:08.510 align:middle line:84%
off their Wall Street
buildings back then.

00:04:08.510 --> 00:04:10.670 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Because they weren't
being bailed out, yeah.

00:04:10.670 --> 00:04:12.128 align:middle line:84%
>>YIAMOUYIANNIS:
They were tanking.

00:04:12.128 --> 00:04:15.620 align:middle line:84%
I mean, much of the
monetary policy we had now

00:04:15.620 --> 00:04:20.120 align:middle line:84%
was ostensibly sold to prevent
the kinds of huge swings.

00:04:20.120 --> 00:04:23.210 align:middle line:90%
The central reserve was only--

00:04:23.210 --> 00:04:24.650 align:middle line:90%
it was in 1907--

00:04:24.650 --> 00:04:27.860 align:middle line:90%
something in that order, 1907--

00:04:27.860 --> 00:04:29.070 align:middle line:90%
I think it started in 1913.

00:04:29.070 --> 00:04:29.870 align:middle line:90%
I think--

00:04:29.870 --> 00:04:30.920 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: '13,
Federal Reserve, yeah.

00:04:30.920 --> 00:04:32.628 align:middle line:84%
>>YIAMOUYIANNIS: --was
officially formed,

00:04:32.628 --> 00:04:35.240 align:middle line:84%
but you know, the Jekyll Island,
and the behind the scenes

00:04:35.240 --> 00:04:37.350 align:middle line:84%
happened a few
years before that.

00:04:37.350 --> 00:04:41.570 align:middle line:84%
But what that turned
into was a guarantor,

00:04:41.570 --> 00:04:43.070 align:middle line:84%
and it was formed
by the very elite

00:04:43.070 --> 00:04:45.230 align:middle line:90%
in society for their wealth.

00:04:45.230 --> 00:04:48.908 align:middle line:84%
They were not going to be caught
with their pants down again,

00:04:48.908 --> 00:04:51.200 align:middle line:84%
even if they're-- because
they're the ones owning a lot

00:04:51.200 --> 00:04:54.140 align:middle line:84%
of this stuff, what they were
going to do is create a system

00:04:54.140 --> 00:04:56.570 align:middle line:84%
that could, quote,
"stabilize the economy."

00:04:56.570 --> 00:04:57.950 align:middle line:90%
But who did it end up helping?

00:04:57.950 --> 00:05:00.890 align:middle line:84%
Well, we know that,
as that has evolved

00:05:00.890 --> 00:05:03.110 align:middle line:90%
to this post-COVID economy.

00:05:03.110 --> 00:05:06.320 align:middle line:84%
Literally trillions just got
siphoned out of Main Street,

00:05:06.320 --> 00:05:08.090 align:middle line:84%
went to Wall Street
and to corporations.

00:05:08.090 --> 00:05:10.632 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And as you said, what
happened with that money that

00:05:10.632 --> 00:05:12.980 align:middle line:84%
was supposed to be used to
pump up the infrastructure,

00:05:12.980 --> 00:05:16.220 align:middle line:84%
help retain jobs for those
who were on the margin.

00:05:16.220 --> 00:05:18.350 align:middle line:84%
Even within those
corporations, a lot of it

00:05:18.350 --> 00:05:22.610 align:middle line:84%
went back into buying
back their own stocks

00:05:22.610 --> 00:05:27.080 align:middle line:84%
to give an illusion of
the company's growth.

00:05:27.080 --> 00:05:28.205 align:middle line:90%
But it was all an illusion.

00:05:28.205 --> 00:05:29.163 align:middle line:90%
>>YIAMOUYIANNIS: Right.

00:05:29.163 --> 00:05:30.590 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: But let
me ask you this.

00:05:30.590 --> 00:05:31.770 align:middle line:90%
It was an illusion.

00:05:31.770 --> 00:05:33.890 align:middle line:84%
They were buying back
their own stocks,

00:05:33.890 --> 00:05:36.570 align:middle line:84%
but since A, a lot of
people weren't aware of it,

00:05:36.570 --> 00:05:39.950 align:middle line:84%
so if you have people investors,
which compared to algorithm

00:05:39.950 --> 00:05:45.560 align:middle line:84%
investment, how does that work
with algorithms when it appears

00:05:45.560 --> 00:05:48.230 align:middle line:84%
a company has just raised
their value because all

00:05:48.230 --> 00:05:50.942 align:middle line:84%
of these stocks trades
and its in-house trading?

00:05:50.942 --> 00:05:52.400 align:middle line:84%
How does that work
with algorithms?

00:05:52.400 --> 00:05:55.730 align:middle line:84%
>>YIAMOUYIANNIS: Well, the
market only responds to demand.

00:05:55.730 --> 00:06:00.440 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't ask for what
the quality of that demand,

00:06:00.440 --> 00:06:02.990 align:middle line:84%
or whether or not
it's funny money,

00:06:02.990 --> 00:06:05.700 align:middle line:84%
or if it's real money saved from
real people, retail investors.

00:06:05.700 --> 00:06:08.120 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So the algorithms
are buy, buy, buy.

00:06:08.120 --> 00:06:10.230 align:middle line:84%
>>YIAMOUYIANNIS: Well, a
lot of these algorithms,

00:06:10.230 --> 00:06:11.710 align:middle line:84%
including high
frequency trading,

00:06:11.710 --> 00:06:13.810 align:middle line:84%
are built to
purposely manipulate

00:06:13.810 --> 00:06:16.180 align:middle line:84%
the market by
either selling a lot

00:06:16.180 --> 00:06:18.430 align:middle line:84%
or selling shorts where
you don't even have it,

00:06:18.430 --> 00:06:21.560 align:middle line:84%
but you create a signal to the
market that it's being sold,

00:06:21.560 --> 00:06:25.157 align:middle line:84%
so you depress it so that
you can win a bet going down.

00:06:25.157 --> 00:06:26.740 align:middle line:84%
They're doing the
same thing going up.

00:06:26.740 --> 00:06:30.130 align:middle line:84%
I call it naked long buying
instead of naked short selling,

00:06:30.130 --> 00:06:35.350 align:middle line:84%
where you literally get zero
interest money, infinite money

00:06:35.350 --> 00:06:37.480 align:middle line:84%
almost, to buy up
your own stocks

00:06:37.480 --> 00:06:39.010 align:middle line:90%
and other stocks in the market.

00:06:39.010 --> 00:06:40.990 align:middle line:84%
And the Fed has
even sent a signal

00:06:40.990 --> 00:06:44.710 align:middle line:84%
that they're willing to
buy up stocks themselves

00:06:44.710 --> 00:06:46.960 align:middle line:84%
in order to keep the
stock market afloat,

00:06:46.960 --> 00:06:48.677 align:middle line:90%
regardless of what value it has.

00:06:48.677 --> 00:06:49.760 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: That's not fair.

00:06:49.760 --> 00:06:51.052 align:middle line:90%
>>YIAMOUYIANNIS: It's not fair.

00:06:51.052 --> 00:06:52.120 align:middle line:90%
It's not fair at all.

00:06:52.120 --> 00:06:54.710 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't have any
fundamentals to it.

00:06:54.710 --> 00:06:57.490 align:middle line:84%
But if you pump money,
whether it's funny money,

00:06:57.490 --> 00:06:59.860 align:middle line:84%
whether it's printed
money or it's real money,

00:06:59.860 --> 00:07:01.890 align:middle line:90%
the market responds the same.

00:07:01.890 --> 00:07:02.690 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: The same.

00:07:02.690 --> 00:07:05.560 align:middle line:84%
So you said also that
for the first time

00:07:05.560 --> 00:07:08.830 align:middle line:84%
in its 107-year
history, they began

00:07:08.830 --> 00:07:12.875 align:middle line:84%
buying up non-investment-grade
junk bonds.

00:07:12.875 --> 00:07:13.750 align:middle line:90%
>>YIAMOUYIANNIS: Yep.

00:07:13.750 --> 00:07:15.610 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So they weren't
even buying real--

00:07:15.610 --> 00:07:17.567 align:middle line:90%
I mean, valuable assets at all.

00:07:17.567 --> 00:07:18.400 align:middle line:90%
>>YIAMOUYIANNIS: No.

00:07:18.400 --> 00:07:20.710 align:middle line:84%
The whole point of
a market, and we'll

00:07:20.710 --> 00:07:23.740 align:middle line:84%
talk about other ways in which
the traditional market has

00:07:23.740 --> 00:07:26.560 align:middle line:84%
completely fallen,
has become a joke,

00:07:26.560 --> 00:07:30.100 align:middle line:90%
is that you have risk, OK?

00:07:30.100 --> 00:07:33.280 align:middle line:84%
People talk about moral hazard,
like if you don't punish people

00:07:33.280 --> 00:07:35.620 align:middle line:84%
that have invested unwisely,
then they'll go ahead

00:07:35.620 --> 00:07:38.080 align:middle line:84%
and they'll take
advantage more and more

00:07:38.080 --> 00:07:40.630 align:middle line:84%
and use kind of a crooked
or unbalanced system.

00:07:40.630 --> 00:07:44.590 align:middle line:84%
But that's an example of exactly
how the market is broken.

00:07:44.590 --> 00:07:48.570 align:middle line:84%
A market is supposed
to reward risk,

00:07:48.570 --> 00:07:51.300 align:middle line:84%
and you're supposed to have
your own money behind it.

00:07:51.300 --> 00:07:53.400 align:middle line:84%
Just like an entrepreneur,
if you win, you win,

00:07:53.400 --> 00:07:54.490 align:middle line:90%
you lose you lose.

00:07:54.490 --> 00:07:56.940 align:middle line:84%
You learn, you move on,
and you get better at it

00:07:56.940 --> 00:07:58.380 align:middle line:90%
and you go back.

00:07:58.380 --> 00:08:02.420 align:middle line:84%
Now, there is basically a
policy over the government

00:08:02.420 --> 00:08:04.920 align:middle line:84%
and the Fed, and this is not
just true in the United States,

00:08:04.920 --> 00:08:07.350 align:middle line:84%
but the whole world
over, to never allow

00:08:07.350 --> 00:08:09.450 align:middle line:90%
a bear market again.

00:08:09.450 --> 00:08:11.550 align:middle line:84%
So literally, we will
lower interest rates

00:08:11.550 --> 00:08:13.020 align:middle line:90%
to 0% for 12 years.

00:08:13.020 --> 00:08:15.330 align:middle line:84%
We will pump money
in, whatever it takes.

00:08:15.330 --> 00:08:18.570 align:middle line:84%
We'll buy up
non-investment-grade junk

00:08:18.570 --> 00:08:21.510 align:middle line:84%
bonds, the very thing
that you invest in

00:08:21.510 --> 00:08:24.600 align:middle line:84%
because they're high risk, high
return, and the very thing you

00:08:24.600 --> 00:08:27.250 align:middle line:84%
should never have
a guarantee on.

00:08:27.250 --> 00:08:31.080 align:middle line:84%
They're now guaranteeing it,
because their constituency

00:08:31.080 --> 00:08:34.320 align:middle line:84%
is no longer the market
itself or any fundamentals.

00:08:34.320 --> 00:08:35.520 align:middle line:90%
It has no bearings, yeah.

00:08:35.520 --> 00:08:37.440 align:middle line:84%
